t, as has been argued, throwbacks to a premodern era. She argues instead that Qur’an schools share a pedagogical frame with today’s Christian and Muslim schools, a connection that plays out the long history of this colonial encounter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChurch schoolszIndiazBengalxHistory. 0aEducationzIndiazBengalxHistory. 0aHindusxEducationzIndiazBengalxHistory. 0aMissionsxEducational workzIndiazBengal. 0aMuslimsxEducationzIndiazBengalxHistory. 0aMuslimszIndiazBengalxEducationxHistory. 0aSecularizationzIndiazBengal. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  abengal.  achristianity.  acolonial india.  acolonialism.  acomparative religion.  acontemporary perspective.  aglobal christianity.  ahinduism.  ahindus.  ahistorical.  aimperialism.  aislam.  amissionaries.  amissionary schools.  amodern education.  amodernization.  amuslims.  anonfiction.  apedagogical.  apolitical.  aquran schools.  areligious education.  areligious historians.  areligious leaders.  areligious scholars.  areligious studies.  aretrospective.  asecularization.  awestern perspective.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026831940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095041240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520950412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520950412/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY